{"id":"1801.07135","submitter":"James Aaronson","authors":"James Aaronson","title":"Maximising the number of solutions to a linear equation in a set of\n  integers","comments":"18 pages. Corrections in light of comments from referee","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1112/blms.12253","report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO math.NT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Given a linear equation of the form $a_1x_1 + a_2x_2 + a_3x_3 = 0$ with\ninteger coefficients $a_i$, we are interested in maximising the number of\nsolutions to this equation in a set $S \\subseteq \\mathbb{Z}$, for sets $S$ of a\ngiven size.\n  We prove that, for any choice of constants $a_1, a_2$ and $a_3$, the maximum\nnumber of solutions is at least $\\left(\\frac{1}{12} + o(1)\\right)|S|^2$.\nFurthermore, we show that this is optimal, in the following sense. For any\n$\\varepsilon > 0,$ there are choices of $a_1, a_2$ and $a_3,$ for which any\nlarge set $S$ of integers has at most $\\left(\\frac{1}{12} +\n\\varepsilon\\right)|S|^2$ solutions.\n  For equations in $k \\geq 3$ variables, we also show an analogous result. Set\n$\\sigma_k = \\int_{-\\infty}^{\\infty} (\\frac{\\sin \\pi x}{\\pi x})^k dx.$ Then, for\nany choice of constants $a_1, \\dots, a_k$, there are sets $S$ with at least\n$(\\frac{\\sigma_k}{k^{k-1}} + o(1))|S|^{k-1}$ solutions to $a_1x_1 + \\dots +\na_kx_k = 0$. Moreover, there are choices of coefficients $a_1, \\dots, a_k$ for\nwhich any large set $S$ must have no more than $(\\frac{\\sigma_k}{k^{k-1}} +\n\\varepsilon)|S|^{k-1}$ solutions, for any $\\varepsilon > 0$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 22 Jan 2018 15:24:11 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 24 Jan 2018 11:52:31 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 20 Jun 2018 16:19:54 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Fri, 3 May 2019 12:40:43 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-05-06"}
